  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contracting activity in Washington, FY2026 to date, totals $12.1B in obligations and includes 71,264 awards with an average award size of $170K. Obligations are down 23.4% year over year and current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date). The Department of Defense accounts for the largest share with $8.2B in obligations, followed by the Department of Energy at $2.8B; the remaining top buyers range from $244M to $62.9M. THE BOEING COMPANY is the largest single vendor with $5.8B in obligations, supported by substantial awards in Aircraft Manufacturing, which also totals $5.8B; Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences is the second-largest industry at $1.1B. FY2026 to date obligations of $12.1B compare with prior fiscal-year totals of $15.6B in FY21, $12.1B in FY22, $13B in FY23, $15.4B in FY24, and $15.8B in FY25. The mix of large prime contractors and energy- and defense-related procurement is reflected in the top vendors and industries listed for the state.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "What is driving the concentration of obligations in Washington?",
        "body": "Defense and energy spending dominate the state’s obligations: the Department of Defense accounts for $8.2B and the Department of Energy accounts for $2.8B. Aircraft Manufacturing leads industry obligations at $5.8B and THE BOEING COMPANY accounts for $5.8B in vendor awards, concentrating a large share of the state total. Several large environmental remediation and construction categories also appear among the top industries and vendors, supporting multi‑hundred‑million dollar contracts."
      },
      {
        "heading": "How does FY2026 to date compare with recent fiscal years?",
        "body": "FY2026 to date obligations are $12.1B, which is lower than FY25 ($15.8B) and FY24 ($15.4B) but matches FY22 ($12.1B) and is below FY21 ($15.6B) and FY23 ($13B). Obligations are down 23.4% year over year, and current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date), so the comparison reflects year‑to‑date activity rather than a closed fiscal-year total."
      }
    ]
  },
